===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[criticize]] severely.
#* {{RQ:King James Version|book=Matthew|chapter=11|verse=20|passage=Then began he to '''upbraid''' the cities wherein most of his mighty works were done, because they repented not:}}
#* {{RQ:Sidney Arcadia2}}
#*: How much doth thy kindness '''upbraid''' my wickedness!
# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic|followed by ''with'' or ''for'', and formerly ''of'' before the object}} To charge with something wrong or disgraceful; to [[reproach]]
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Coriolanus|V|i|passage=Yet do not '''upbraid''' us our distress.}}
#* {{RQ:King James Version|book=Mark|chapter=16|verse=14|passage=Afterward he appeared unto the eleven as they sat at meat, and '''upbraided''' them with their unbelief and hardness of heart, because they believed not them which had seen him after he was risen.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To treat with [[contempt]].
#* {{RQ:Spenser Faerie Queene|1|5}}
#*:There also was that mighty monarch laid, Low under all, yet above all in pride; That name of native fire did foul '''upbraid''', And would, as Ammon's son, be magnify'd.
# {{lb|en|obsolete|followed by "to" before the object}} To object or urge as a matter of [[reproach]]
#: {{syn|en|cast up}}
#* {{RQ:Bacon Of Envy}}
#*:Those that have been bred together, are more apt to envy their equals when raised: for it doth '''upbraid''' unto them their own fortunes, and pointeth at them.
# {{lb|en|archaic|intransitive}} To utter upbraidings.
# {{lb|en|UK|_|dialectal|Northern England|archaic}} To [[vomit]]; [[retch]].

